SIMPLE: provisor
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Provisor
<hw>Pro*vi"sor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr.
<ets>providere</ets>: cf. F. <ets>proviseur</ets>. See
<er>Provide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who provides; a
purveyor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The chief <xex>provisor</xex>
of our horse.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ford.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The purveyor,
steward, or treasurer of a religious house.</def> <au>Cowell.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>One who is regularly inducted into a benefice. See
<er>Provision</er>, 5.</def> <au>P. Plowman.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Hist.)</fld> <def>One who procures or receives
a papal provision. See <er>Provision</er>, 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provisorily</ent>⟦br⟧
